@startmindmap
* Advanced GNU/Linux\nSecurity
** Program <-> kernel
*** syscalls (synchronous)
*** signals (async, SIGKILL/SIGSEGV)
*** strace to observe
** Problem
*** a process can call ALL syscalls
*** execution not fixed\n(buffer overflow, hidden options)
*** UNIX rule #2: do one thing well
** SECCOMP
*** Andrea Arcangeli, 2005
*** mode 1 strict\n(exit/sigreturn/read/write)
*** mode 2 seccomp-bpf (filters)
*** whitelist / blacklist
*** adopters: Chrome, Firefox,\nOpenSSH, qemu
*** needs recompile, arch-dependent
** LSM (framework)
*** hooks on kernel functions
*** generic interface (2002)
*** DAC vs MAC (TCSEC, 1993)
** SELinux
*** NSA, MLS from MULTICS
*** type enforcement\nuser:role:type:range
*** labels via extended attributes
*** Disabled/Permissive/Enforcing
*** most complete, hardest
** AppArmor
*** path-based (not inodes)
*** profiles in /etc/apparmor.d/
*** enforce / complain modes
*** simpler, no labels
** Other LSMs
*** SMACK, TOMOYO
*** Yama, LoadPin, SafeSetID, Lockdown
*** stackable (major/minor)
** Takeaway
*** many adversary models\n-> complex tool suite
*** MULTICS syndrome (entropy up)
*** castle model no longer enough
*** least privilege -> defense in depth\n-> isolation/virtualization
@endmindmap
